<P>
CHENEY VOWS TO WORK FOR ISRAEL AID 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Defense Secretary Dick Cheney promised visiting Israeli Defense Minister 
Yitzhak Rabin today to try to keep U.S. military aid to Israel at $1.8 billion 
next year despite Pentagon budget cuts. 
</P>
<P>
"Mr. Rabin expressed an interest in seeing that the United States maintain its 
military commitment to Israel," a U.S. defense official said after Rabin and 
Cheney met for more than an hour at the Defense Department, and Cheney "said he 
would do his best." 
</P>
<P>
The Bush Administration has asked Congress to keep total U.S. aid to Israel at 
its current level in fiscal 1990, beginning in October -- $1.8 billion in 
military assistance and $1.2 billion in economic support. 
</P>
